HAND, FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - INDIA: (MAHARASHTRA) ETIOLOGIC AGENTS
******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 23 Nov 2013
Source: The Times of India, Pune [edited]
http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-11-23/pune/44389035_1_niv-samples-mouth-ulcers


Scientists from the [Pune]city-based National Institute of Virology (NIV) have confirmed the presence of enterovirus which, they said, has been causing hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) in children in Pune [Maharashtra state; the city was formerly known as Poona]. The contagious viral illness has been spreading among children below 5 years of age in the last 2 months. Of the 79 samples drawn by the scientists, 40 per cent tested positive for enterovirus.

"The circulating virus in the city, causing HFMD in infants and children, is enterovirus. The infection caused by the virus is usually mild. Hence, there is no need to panic," said senior scientist D T Mourya, director of NIV. The viral infection, benign but irritating, is characterised by painful rashes along with throat [pain] and fever. Coxsackieviruses and enteroviruses are the major causative agents of HFMD in India. This is the 1st time that the Virology Institute investigated HFMD cases in Pune after doctors reported a spurt [of cases] since October [2013]. Earlier, it had carried out HFMD investigations in Kerala, West Bengal, Odisha, Gujarat and Tamil Nadu in 2009-2010. Scientist V Gopalkrishna, Deputy Director of NIV, who spearheaded the HFMD study along with paediatricians, said, "79 clinical samples comprising throat swabs, rectal swabs, vesicular swabs and blood samples were collected from children below 7 years of age with suspected HFMD in Pune who went to paediatricians' clinics and hospitals for treatment in the last 2 months. Nearly 40 per cent of the samples tested positive for the etiological agent enterovirus. Now, cases are on the decline." Paediatricians from Shaishav clinic, Chiranjeev clinic, Bharati Hospital and Ajinkya Hospital from the city were involved in this study with NIV scientists.

"If a child is not eating and shows loss of appetite and has mouth ulcers, then it is time to consult a doctor," said paediatrician Sharad Agarkhedkar. Paediatrician Jayant Navarange, who is part of the NIV study and has been treating kids with HFMD in the last 2 months, said, "HFMD is contagious. Hence, infected children should stay away from schools till they completely recover," he added.

[Byline: Umesh Isalkar]

