Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[HFMD is a common viral illness that usually affects infants and children younger than 5 years old. However, it can sometimes occur in adults. Symptoms of HFMD include fever, blister-like sores in the mouth (herpangina) and a skin rash. HFMD is caused by viruses that belong to the genus _Enterovirus_. This group of viruses includes polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, echoviruses, and enteroviruses. Coxsackievirus A16 is the most common cause of HFMD in the United States, but other coxsackieviruses have been associated with the illness. Enterovirus 71 has been associated with more severe outbreaks of HFMD (see: http://www.cdc.gov/hand-foot-mouth/about/index.html).

HFMD is prevalent globally and infects children in all communities. Since normally the infection is mild and of short duration, there has been little incentive to identify the specific etiologic agent. Normally ProMED-mail does not record these outbreaks unless the specific etiologic agent has been identified, or there is some unusual feature. The outbreak in Pune is exceptional in that the etiologic agents have been identified. Curiously the etiologic agent was only identified in less than 40 per cent of cases.

The Western Pacific Region of WHO routinely publishes data on the incidence of HFMD throughout East Asia (but not India) [see: http://www.wpro.who.int/emerging_diseases/HFMD/en/]. The most recent update (13 Nov 2013) reported that HFMD is declining. Hong Kong (China), Macao (China), Japan and Republic of Korea (South Korea) have reported a higher cumulative number of cases in 2013 than in 2012 for the same time period. The recent trend, following seasonal patterns, is showing a decrease in China, Hong Kong (China), Macao (China), Japan, Republic of Korea, Singapore and Viet Nam.

China: Monthly average of cases has decreased from September (183 187 cases and 14 deaths) to October (134 032 cases and 8 deaths) 2013. There were 1 651 959 cases with 265 deaths reported up to the end of October in 2013.

Hong Kong (China): Surveillance for HFMD is conducted through sentinel reporting units. Based on the 3 week moving average, weekly trends in hospitalized cases, general practitioners, and general outpatient clinics decreased. In the week 27 Oct to 2 Nov 2013, 4 HFMD inpatients (relative to 5 cases in the same period in 2012) were reported by the Hospital Authority; 0.1 cases per 1000 consultations among general out-patient clinics and 0.9 cases per 1000 consultations among general practitioners.

Macao (China): Weekly trend has decreased based on the 3 week moving average. 19 cases were reported from 29 Oct to 4 Nov 2013 compared with 30 cases in the same period for 2012. The cumulative report for 2013 to the week ending 4 Nov was 2078 cases.

Japan: Surveillance for HFMD is conducted through sentinel reporting units. The weekly trend decreased based on the 3 week moving average. 4071 cases (1.29 cases per sentinel unit) were reported from 14 to 20 Oct 2013 compared with 1998 cases in the same period for 2012. Cumulative total for 2013 to the week ending 20 Oct was 281 149 cases.

Republic of Korea (South Korea): Surveillance for HFMD is conducted through sentinel reporting units. The weekly trend is decreasing based on the 3 week moving average; 3.0 cases per 1000 outpatients for the week ending 5 Oct 2013. Cumulative total for 2013 to the week ending 5 Oct was 6.3 cases per 1000 outpatients.

Singapore: The weekly trend increased based on the 3 week moving average; 914 cases were reported between 27 Oct to 2 Nov 2013 (relative to 265 for the same period in 2012). Cumulative total for 2013 to the week ending 2 Nov 2013 was 26 473 cases.

Viet Nam: The weekly number of reported cases during 7 to 13 Oct 2013 was 1610 relative to 1656 during the previous week. 63 109 cases with 19 deaths have been reported from across 63 provinces up to 13 Oct 2013.

It is unfortunate that there is so little determination of the etiologic agent(s) involved.

For further information on the HFMD situation or its surveillance, please visit the following links:
China (in Chinese): http://www.moh.gov.cn/wsb/pyqxx/list.shtml
Hong Kong (China): http://www.chp.gov.hk/en/data/1/26/44/292/1303.html
Japan: http://www.nih.go.jp/niid/en/survaillance-data-table-english.html
Republic of Korea: http://www.cdc.go.kr/CDC/info/CdcKrInfo0301.jsp?menuIds=HOME001-MNU0004-MNU0036-MNU0037&q_type=B&q_value=2013
